<paragraph id="8BE236F59D64FFD3FF02FC4333BCFBF8" blockId="24.[168,775,941,1065]" pageId="24" pageNumber="675">
<emphasis id="B929EAE79D64FFD3FF02FC4330EAFC14" bold="true" box="[168,465,941,965]" pageId="24" pageNumber="675">Distribution and ecology.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="F34A76659D64FFD3FE71FC43337CFC14" box="[475,583,941,965]" name="Colombia" pageId="24" pageNumber="675">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F34A76659D64FFD3FDFFFC4333E9FC14" box="[597,722,941,965]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="24" pageNumber="675">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="F34A76659D64FFD3FF02FC21303AFC37" box="[168,257,975,998]" name="Panama" pageId="24" pageNumber="675">Panama</collectingCountry>
. This species grows in semideciduous and evergreen forests of Cerro Pirre. It represents an uncommon species, usually found in semi-shaded areas.
</paragraph>
